                <h2>Define the Budget</h2>

                <hr class="brief--hr">
                <p><strong>Calculating the budget for SEO depends on various factors, including the nature of your business, the current state of the website, and strategic goals. Here are several main types of budget calculation for SEO:</strong></p>

                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Fixed Budget:</strong>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Description:</strong> Here you have a fixed amount allocated for SEO over a specific period, for example, monthly or yearly.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong> Convenient for planning, cost predictability.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> May require adjustments if additional work is needed.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Stage Payments:</strong>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Description:</strong> Work is divided into stages, and payment is made upon completion of each stage.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong> Allows controlling the process and quality of work.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> May require more detailed planning and deadline control.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Performance-Based:</strong>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Description:</strong> Payment is made based on achieved results, such as increased traffic or positions in search results.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong> More direct link between expenses and actual results.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> It can be challenging to estimate the real cost of work at the initial stage.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Daily/Weekly/Monthly Rates:</strong>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Description:</strong> Payment is based on the number of hours worked or the volume of work completed in a specific period.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong> Suitable for projects with irregular or variable workloads.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Requires careful tracking and control.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Competition-Based Budget:</strong>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Description:</strong> The budget calculation depends on the competitiveness of your industry in search results.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong> Adapted to the level of competition, more flexible.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Requires constant monitoring of competitors and the market.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Mixed Budget:</strong>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Description:</strong> Using a combination of different budget calculation methods depending on specific tasks and project stages.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Advantages:</strong> Allows for more flexible responses to changes in project conditions.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <strong>Disadvantages:</strong> Requires more complex management and control.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <p>
                    <strong>Each of these approaches has its advantages and disadvantages, and the right choice depends on the specific requirements of your business, its current state, and strategic goals.</strong>
                </p>

